 1483","1438":"1438","1504":"1504","Toddington, Bedfordshire, England":"Toddington, Bedfordshire, England","Broughton, Lancashire, England":"Broughton, Lancashire, England","England":"England","Denston, Suffolk, England":"Denston, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Broughton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the many places in all parts of England called Broughton. The first element is variously Old English <i>brōc</i> ‘brook’, <i>burg</i> ‘fortress’, or <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’; the second is in all cases Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Braughton","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Broughton  ."]},{"name":"Brought","meanings":["English: shortened form of   Broughton  .","Americanized form of German   Braucht  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Broughton was born in 1466, in Toddington, Bedfordshire, England, his